# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aachener-zeitung
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] During the first three years of the station, it profiled itself as a pop, rock and urban station aimed at a young audience.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] Due to a lack of success, the station dropped the format in mid-2008 and many presenters were dismissed.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] The station started focusing on nederpop and "soft" music, and would add "women-friendly" programs, with presenters such as Daphne Deckers, Myrna Goossen, Tanja Jess, and Elsemiek Hillen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] Today, 100% NL runs the music of the Netherlands.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] Core artists include Jan Smit, Nick & Simon, 3JS, Ilse Delange, Doe Maar, Bløf, Acda en De Munnik, Paul de Leeuw, Marco Borsato, Anouk, and Guus Meeuwis.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] In addition, listeners can hear artists like Armin van Buuren, Mr.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] The station also includes music from other countries; listeners can hear hits from artists such as Robbie Williams, Phil Collins, and UB40.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] The emergence of 100% NL characterized by numerous lawsuits.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] In 2003, the Dutch radio frequencies were re-distributed based on zero base, a redistribution of the AM and FM frequencies with the aim to offer more commercial radio stations access to the Dutch airwaves.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] This distribution is a comparative test with auction element.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] European companies could apply for these frequencies and had to submit a business plan for the desired frequency.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] A number of national frequency packages (lots) were made available by the government without any conditions, called "plots".
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] The "special stipulations plots" are packages which have conditions were set.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] For this special stipulations except plots had a business plan also be handed a program plan.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] The plans submitted were compared by an independent committee (comparative test).
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] If a package no special stipulations of the applications are head and shoulders above the rest would stabbing, the applicant for the financial bid would be the deciding factor (the auction element).
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] One of these plots was designated by the government for music of Dutch and European soil, the so-called plot A9.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] RTL Netherlands offered 35% Dutch language productions, while Media Sales 70% boosted in that category.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] The review committee found that this difference "not significant" was, after the financial bid of 23 million euros of RTL against the 8,000 euros of the Finnish Media Sales was decisive and RTL FM came on the air.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] Media Sales, led by (then) ANP newsreader Herbert Fisher, then went to court.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] After two years of proceedings on the merits of the court ruled The Hague Finnish Media Sales in the same.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] Eventually 100% NL on 8 July 2006 beginning with the first broadcast.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] In 2009 100% NL was nominated for a Marconi Award.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] On the night of 7 to 8 July 2006, the start of the program began with a broadcast from the boiler house at the Westergasfabriek Terrain in Amsterdam.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] DJs Eline la Croix and Casper Meijer presented the live show with urban artists like K-Liber 4 Life, The Opposites, and Ninthe.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] The first song played was "The Right Side Won" by What Fun! and was preceded by a speech by 100% NL spokesman Herbert Visser.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] 100% NL TV is a television channel which started in 2013 as a TV channel of 100% NL.
[src:aachener-zeitung/100-nl] In addition, the station has a number of digital channels that link to 100% NL, like 100% NL Dance, 100% NL Feest, and 100% NL Liefde.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The once Celtic settlement was equipped with several *thermae* in the course of colonization by Roman pioneers settling at the warm Aachen thermal springs around the 1st century.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] After the withdrawal of the Roman troops, the vicus *Aquae Granni* was Frankized around the 5th century, by which it came under Merovingian and later Carolingian rule.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] With the completion of the Carolingian Palace of Aachen at the transition to the 9th century, Aachen was constituted as the main royal residence of the Frankish Empire ruled by Charlemagne.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Because of that, the city is sometimes called the "cradle of Europe".
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] After the Treaty of Verdun, the city was within the borders of Middle Francia, until it became part of East Francia after the Treaty of Meerssen (870).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] It subsequently was part of the Holy Roman Empire and was granted city rights in 1166 by Emperor Frederick Barbarossa, becoming an imperial city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] It served as the coronation site where 31 Holy Roman Emperors were crowned Kings of the Germans from 936 to 1531, until Frankfurt became the preferred place of coronation.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] One of Germany's leading institutes of higher education in technology, the RWTH Aachen University *(Rheinisch-Westfälisch Technische Hochschule Aachen)*, is located in the city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Its university hospital Uniklinikum Aachen is Europe's largest single-building hospital.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen's industries include science, engineering and information technology.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 2009, Aachen was ranked eighth among cities in Germany for innovation.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen is located at the northern foothills of the High Fens and the Eifel Mountains.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] It sits on the Wurm River, a tributary of the Rur, and together with Mönchengladbach, it is the only larger German city in the drainage basin of the Meuse.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The regional dialect spoken in the city is a Central Franconian, Ripuarian variant with strong Limburgish influences from the dialects in the neighbouring Netherlands.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] As a Rhenish city, Aachen is one of the main centres of carnival celebrations in Germany, along with Cologne and Mainz.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The culinary specialty for which the city is best known is Aachener Printen, a type of gingerbread.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The name *Aachen* is a modern descendant, like southern German *Ach(e)*, German: *Aach*, meaning "river" or "stream", from Old High German *ahha*, meaning "water" or "stream", which directly translates (and etymologically corresponds) to Latin *Aquae*, referring to the springs.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The location has been inhabited by humans since the Neolithic era, about 5,000 years ago, attracted to its warm mineral springs.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Latin *Aquae* figures in Aachen's Roman name *Aquae granni*, which meant "waters of Grannus", referring to the Celtic god of healing who was worshipped at the springs.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] This word became *Åxhe* in Walloon and *Aix* in French, and subsequently *Aix-la-Chapelle* to distinguish it from Aix-en-Provence, after Charlemagne had his palatine chapel built there in the late 8th century and then made the city his empire's capital.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Flint quarries on the Lousberg, Schneeberg, and Königshügel, first used during Neolithic times (3000–2500 BC), attest to the long occupation of the site of Aachen, as do recent finds under the modern city's *Elisengarten* pointing to a former settlement from the same period.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Bronze Age (around 1600 BC) settlement is evidenced by the remains of barrows (burial mounds) found, for example, on the Klausberg.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] During the Iron Age, the area was settled by Celtic peoples who were perhaps drawn by the marshy Aachen basin's hot sulphur springs where they worshipped Grannus, god of light and healing.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Proofs of a Celts settlements on Aachens territories at the beginning of the Gallic War do not exist at the moment.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The 25-hectare Roman spa resort town of Aquae Granni was, according to legend, founded by Grenus, under Hadrian, around 124 AD.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Grenus refers to the Celtic god, and it seems it was the Roman 6th Legion at the start of the 1st century AD that first channelled the hot springs into a spa at Büchel, adding at the end of the same century the *Münstertherme* spa, two water pipelines, and a probable sanctuary dedicated to Grannus.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] A kind of forum, surrounded by colonnades, connected the two spa complexes.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] There was an extensive residential area.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The Romans built bathhouses near Burtscheid.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] A temple precinct called *Vernenum* was built near the modern Kornelimünster/Walheim.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Today, remains have been found of three bathhouses, including two fountains in the *Elisenbrunnen* and the Burtscheid bathhouse.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Roman civil administration in Aachen eventually broke down as the baths and other public buildings (along with most of the villae rusticae of the surrounding countryside) were destroyed around AD 375 at the start of the migration period.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The last Roman coin finds are from the time of Emperor Gratian (AD 375–383).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Rome withdrew its troops from the area, but the town remained populated.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] By 470, the town came to be ruled by the Ripuarian Franks and subordinated to their capital, Cologne.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] During the Roman period, Aachen was the site of a flourishing Jewish community.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Pepin the Short had a castle residence built in the town, due to the proximity of the hot springs and also for strategic reasons as it is located between the Rhineland and northern France.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In the year of his coronation as king of the Franks, 768, Charlemagne came to spend Christmas at Aachen for the first time.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] He remained there in a mansion which he may have extended, although there is no source attesting to any significant building activity at Aachen in his time, apart from the building of the Palatine Chapel (since 1930, cathedral) and the Palace.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Charlemagne spent most winters in Aachen between 792 and his death in 814.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen became the focus of his court and the political centre of his empire.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] During the Carolingian empire, a Jewish community lived near the royal palace.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In Jewish texts, the city of Aachen was called *Aish* or *Ash* (אש).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 797, Isaac, a Jewish merchant, accompanied two ambassadors of Charlemagne to the court of Harun al-Rashid.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] He returned to Aachen in July 802, bearing an elephant called Abul-Abbas as a gift for the emperor.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] By the terms of the Treaty of Verdun 834, Aachen became part of Middle Francia, governed by emperor Lothair.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] He was succeeded by Lothair II as king of Lotharingia by the terms of the Treaty of Prüm.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] By the Treaty of Meerssen 870, Aachen came to East Francia.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Within East Francia, later the Holy Roman Empire until 1166, Aachen was part of the Duchy of Lower Lotharingia.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 936, Otto I was crowned king of East Francia in the collegiate church built by Charlemagne.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] During the reign of Otto II, the nobles revolted and the West Franks under Lothair raided Aachen in 978.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen was attacked again by Odo of Champagne, who attacked the imperial palace while Conrad II was absent.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Odo relinquished it and was killed afterwards.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The palace and town of Aachen had fortifying walls built by order of Emperor Frederick Barbarossa between 1172 and 1176.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Over the next 500 years, most kings of Germany who ruled the Holy Roman Empire were crowned in Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The original audience hall built by Charlemagne was torn down and replaced by the current city hall in 1330.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] During the 13th century, many Jews converted to Christianity, as shown in the records of the Aachen Minster (today's Cathedral).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 1486, the Jews of Aachen offered gifts to Maximilian I during his coronation ceremony.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The last king to be crowned here was Ferdinand I in 1531.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] During the Middle Ages, Aachen remained a city of regional importance, due to its proximity to Flanders; it achieved a modest position in the trade in woollen cloths, favoured by imperial privilege.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The city remained a free imperial city, subject to the emperor only, but was politically far too weak to influence the policies of any of its neighbours.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The only dominion it had was over Burtscheid, a neighbouring territory ruled by a Benedictine abbess, which was forced to accept that all of its traffic must pass through the "Aachener Reich".
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] As an imperial city, Aachen held certain political privileges that allowed it to remain independent of the troubles of Europe for many years.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] It remained a direct vassal of the Holy Roman Empire throughout most of the Middle Ages.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] It was also the site of many important church councils, including the Council of 837 and the Council of 1166, a council convened by the antipope Paschal III.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Parts of Aachen belonged to Imperial Abbey of Burtscheid, Reichsabtei Kornelimünster, Duchy of Juelich and the Duchy of Limburg.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen was an important site for the production of historical manuscripts.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Under Charlemagne's purview, both the Ada Gospels and the Coronation Gospels may have been produced in Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In addition, quantities of the other texts in the court library were also produced locally.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] During the reign of Louis the Pious (814–840), substantial quantities of ancient texts were produced at Aachen, including legal manuscripts such as the leges scriptorium group, patristic texts including the five manuscripts of the Bamberg Pliny Group.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Finally, under Lothair I (840–855), texts of outstanding quality were still being produced.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] This however marked the end of the period of manuscript production at Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 1598, following the invasion of Spanish troops from the Netherlands, Rudolf deposed all Protestant office holders in Aachen and went as far as expelling them from the city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] From the early 16th century, Aachen started to lose its power and influence.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] First the coronations of emperors were moved from Aachen to Frankfurt.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] 1614 Aachen became theatre of the Siege of Aachen (1614) within the War of the Jülich Succession.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Although religious changes were forced several times in Aachen and Protestant communities were banned, hardly any fighting took place during the Thirty Years' War.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The religious wars had been followed by the great fire of 1656.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] After the destruction of most of the city in 1656, the rebuilding was mostly in the Baroque style.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The decline of Aachen culminated in 1794, when the French, led by General Charles Dumouriez, occupied Aachen..
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The area of Aachen had been scene of battles within the Flanders Campaign in autumn 1794: Battle of Ourthe, Battle of Aldenhoven, Siege of Maastricht.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 1542, the Dutch humanist and physician Francis Fabricius published his study of the health benefits of the hot springs in Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] By the middle of the 17th century, the city had developed a considerable reputation as a spa, although this was in part because Aachen was then – and remained well into the 19th and early 20th century – a place of high-level prostitution.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Traces of this hidden agenda of the city's history are found in the 18th-century guidebooks to Aachen as well as to the other spas.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The main indication for visiting patients, ironically, was syphilis; only by the end of the 19th century had rheumatism become the most important object of cures at Aachen and Burtscheid.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen was chosen as the site of several important congresses and peace treaties: the first congress of Aachen (often referred to as the Congress of Aix-la-Chapelle in English) on 2 May 1668, leading to the First Treaty of Aachen in the same year which ended the War of Devolution.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The second congress ended with the second treaty in 1748, ending the War of the Austrian Succession.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 1789, there was a constitutional crisis in the Aachen government, and in 1794 Aachen lost its status as a free imperial city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 1629, the Aachen Jewish community was expelled from the city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 1667, six Jews were allowed to return.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Most of the Aachen Jewish community settled in Burtscheid.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] As recently as the late 18th century the Abbess of Burtscheid was still prevented from building a road linking her territory to the neighbouring estates of the duke of Jülich; the city of Aachen deployed its handful of soldiers to chase away road-diggers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] On 9 February 1801, the Peace of Lunéville removed the ownership of Aachen and the entire "left bank" of the Rhine from Germany (the Holy Roman Empire) and granted it to France.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 1815, control of the town was passed to the Kingdom of Prussia through an agreement reached by the Congress of Vienna.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The third congress took place in 1818, to decide the fate of occupied Napoleonic France.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The current territory of Aachen belonged entirely to the Arrondissement d'Aix-la-Chapelle.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 1815, after the Second Treaty of Paris, finishing the Napoleonic Wars, the Kingdom of Prussia took over within the new German Confederation.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The city was one of its most socially and politically backward centres until the end of the 19th century.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The Kingdom of Prussia created the "Regierungsbezirk Aachen" (governmental district) and integrated it into the Prussian province Grand Duchy of the Lower Rhine, from 1822 the Rhine Province.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Starting in 1838, the railway from Cologne to Belgium passed through Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] By "Gesetz betreffend die Vereinigung der Stadtgemeinde Burtscheid mit der Stadtgemeinde Aachen vom 29.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] März 1897 nebst Vertrag" Aachen and Burtscheid merged 1897.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The city suffered extreme overcrowding and deplorable sanitary conditions until 1875, when the medieval fortifications were abandoned as a limit to building and new, better housing was built in the east of the city, where sanitary drainage was easiest.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In December 1880, the Aachen tramway network was opened, and in 1895 it was electrified.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In the 19th century and up to the 1930s, the city was important in the production of railway locomotives and carriages, iron, pins, needles, buttons, tobacco, woollen goods, and silk goods.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen was enlarged 1 April 1906 by "Gesetz betreffend die Vereinigung der Gemeinde Forst mit der Stadtgemeinde Aachen vom 31.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] März 1906 nebst Vertrag" by incorporation of Forst.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The Belgium Campaign within World War I started in Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] After World War I, Aachen was occupied by the Entente until 1930, along with the rest of German territory west of the Rhine.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen was one of the locations involved in the Rhenish Republic.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] On 21 October 1923, an armed mob took over the city hall.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Similar actions took place in Mönchengladbach, Duisburg, and Krefeld.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] During the interwar period, Aachen was assigned some areas of the former district of Eupen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Also the Western Campaign of World War II started nearby Aachen with the Battle of Maastricht.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen was heavily damaged during World War II.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Blood mentioned more than 120 air strikes on Aachen between 1940 an 1944.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] According to Jörg Friedrich in *The Fire* (2002), two Allied air raids on 11 April and 24 May 1944 "radically destroyed" the city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The first killed 1,525, including 212 children, and bombed six hospitals.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] During the second, 442 aircraft hit two railway stations, killed 207, and left 15,000 homeless.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The raids destroyed Aachen-Eilendorf and Aachen-Burtscheid.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In autumn 1944 Aachen and its surroundings were reached by the Western Allied Siegfried Line campaign.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The city and its fortified surroundings were besieged from 12 September to 21 October 1944 by the US 1st Infantry Division with the 3rd Armored Division assisting from the south.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Around 13 October the US 2nd Armored Division, coming from the north, and got as close as Würselen, while the 30th Infantry Division completed the encirclement of Aachen on 16 October 1944.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] With reinforcements from the US 28th Infantry Division the battle continued involving direct assaults through the heavily defended city, which forced the German garrison to surrender on 21 October 1944.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen was the first German city to be captured by the Western Allies, and its residents welcomed the soldiers as liberators.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] What remained of the city was destroyed—in some areas completely—during the fighting, mostly by American artillery fire and demolitions carried out by the Waffen-SS defenders.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Damaged buildings included medieval churches and the Rathaus (city hall), although Aachen Cathedral was largely unscathed.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] 4,000 inhabitants remained in the city; the rest had followed evacuation orders.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Its first Allied-appointed mayor, Franz Oppenhoff, was assassinated by an SS commando unit.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] On 16 May 1815, the Jewish community of the city offered an homage in its synagogue to the Prussian king, Friedrich Wilhelm III.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 1862, a large synagogue was built, later called the Old Synagogue.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] On *Kristallnacht* in 1938, the synagogue was destroyed.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] By the onset of World War II in 1939, many Jews had emigrated or were arrested, and only 782 remained in the city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] At the end of the war in 1945, only 62 Jews lived in the city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] As of 2003, 1,434 Jews were again living in Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Subsequent the German surrender finishing the Battle of Aachen 21 October 1944, the Supreme Headquarters Allied Expeditionary Force acted as military government.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen within the northern part of Rhine Province became part of British occupation zone in Germany.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen also belonged to the British zone under Belgian control.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] 46, British Military Government created the "Land Nordrhein/Westfalen", including the "Regierungsbezirk Aachen", 23 August 1946.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] 23 May 1949 Aachen became part of the Federal Republic of Germany.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] With the Aachen Law of 1971, Aachen was merged with Kornelimünster, Brand, Walheim, Laurensberg, Richterich, Haaren, Eilendorf.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] After the abolition of the Aachen governmental district, August 1972, Aachen became part of the Cologne governmental district.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen is located in the middle of the Meuse–Rhine Euroregion, close to the border tripoint of Germany, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The town of Vaals in the Netherlands lies nearby at about 6 km (4 mi) from Aachen's city centre, while the Dutch city of Heerlen and Eupen, the capital of the German-speaking Community of Belgium, are both located about 20 km (12 mi) from Aachen city centre.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen lies near the head of the open valley of the Wurm (which today flows through the city in canalised form), part of the larger basin of the Meuse, and about 30 km (19 mi) north of the High Fens, which form the northern edge of the Eifel uplands of the Rhenish Massif.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The maximum dimensions of the city's territory are 21.6 km (13+3⁄8 mi) from north to south, and 17.2 km (10+3⁄4 mi) from east to west.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The highest point in Aachen, located in the far southeast of the city, lies at an elevation of 410 m (1,350 ft) above sea level.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The lowest point, in the north, and on the border with the Netherlands, is at 125 m (410 ft).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] As the westernmost city in Germany (and close to the Low Countries), Aachen and the surrounding area belongs to a temperate climate zone (Cfb), with humid weather, mild winters, and warm summers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Because of its location north of the Eifel and the High Fens and its subsequent prevailing westerly weather patterns, rainfall in Aachen (on average 805 mm/year) is comparatively higher than, for example, in Bonn (with 669 mm/year).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Another factor in the local weather forces of Aachen is the occurrence of Foehn winds on the southerly air currents, which results from the city's geographic location on the northern edge of the Eifel.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Because the city is surrounded by hills, it suffers from inversion-related smog.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Some areas of the city have become urban heat islands as a result of poor heat exchange, both because of the area's natural geography and from human activity.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The city's numerous cold air corridors, which are slated to remain as free as possible from new construction, therefore play an important role in the urban climate of Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The January average is 3.0 °C (37 °F), while the July average is 18.5 °C (65 °F).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Precipitation is almost evenly spread throughout the year.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In the 1991–2020 period, the record latest freeze (at 2 m above ground) of spring occurred on 28 April and the record first fall freeze on 13 October.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The geology of Aachen is very structurally heterogeneous.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The oldest occurring rocks in the area surrounding the city originate from the Devonian period and include carboniferous sandstone, greywacke, claystone and limestone.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] These formations are part of the Rhenish Massif, north of the High Fens.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In the Pennsylvanian subperiod of the Carboniferous geological period, these rock layers were narrowed and folded as a result of the Variscan orogeny.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] After this event, and over the course of the following 200 million years, this area has been continuously flattened.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] During the Cretaceous period, the ocean penetrated the continent from the direction of the North Sea up to the mountainous area near Aachen, bringing with it clay, sand, and chalk deposits.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] While the clay (which was the basis for a major pottery industry in nearby Raeren) is mostly found in the lower areas of Aachen, the hills of the Aachen Forest and the Lousberg were formed from upper Cretaceous sand and chalk deposits.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] More recent sedimentation is mainly located in the north and east of Aachen and was formed through Tertiary and Quaternary river and wind activities.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Along the major thrust fault of the Variscan orogeny, there are over 30 thermal springs in Aachen and Burtscheid.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] At the end of 2009, the foreign-born residents of Aachen made up 13.6 percent of the total population.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] A significant portion of foreign residents are students at the RWTH Aachen University.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen is at the western end of the Benrath line that divides High German to the south from the rest of the West Germanic speech area to the north.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen's local dialect is called *Öcher Platt* and belongs to Ripuarian.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The city is divided into seven administrative districts, or boroughs, each with its own district council, district leader, and district authority.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The councils are elected locally by those who live within the district, and these districts are further subdivided into smaller sections for statistical purposes, with each sub-district named by a two-digit number.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The current mayor of Aachen is Michael Ziemons of the CDU, who was elected in 2025.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The Aachen city council governs the city alongside the mayor.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral was erected on the orders of Charlemagne.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Construction began *c.* AD 796, and it was, on completion *c.* 798, the largest cathedral north of the Alps.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] It was modelled after the Basilica of San Vitale, in Ravenna, Italy, and was built by Odo of Metz.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Charlemagne also desired for the chapel to compete with the Lateran Palace, both in quality and authority.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] It was originally built in the Carolingian style, including marble covered walls, and mosaic inlay on the dome.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] On his death, Charlemagne's remains were interred in the cathedral and can be seen there to this day.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The cathedral was extended several times in later ages, turning it into a curious and unique mixture of building styles.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The throne and gallery portion date from the Ottonian, with portions of the original opus sectile floor still visible.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The 13th century saw gables being added to the roof, and after the fire of 1656, the dome was rebuilt.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Finally, a choir was added around the start of the 15th century.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] After Frederick Barbarossa canonised Charlemagne in 1165 the chapel became a destination for pilgrims.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] For 600 years, from 936 to 1531, Aachen Cathedral was the church of coronation for 30 German kings and 12 queens.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The church built by Charlemagne is still the main attraction of the city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In addition to holding the remains of its founder, it became the burial place of his successor Otto III.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In the upper chamber of the gallery, Charlemagne's marble throne is housed.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral has been designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Most of the marble and columns used in the construction of the cathedral were brought from Rome and Ravenna, including the sarcophagus in which Charlemagne was eventually laid to rest.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] A bronze bear from Gaul was placed inside, along with an equestrian statue from Ravenna, believed to be Theodric, in contrast to a wolf and a statue of Marcus Aurelius in the Capitoline.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Bronze pieces such as the doors and railings, some of which have survived to present day, were cast in a local foundry.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Finally, there is uncertainty surrounding the bronze pine cone in the chapel, and where it was created.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Wherever it was made, it was also a parallel to a piece in Rome, this in Old St.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen Cathedral Treasury has housed, throughout its history, a collection of liturgical objects.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The origin of this church treasure is in dispute as some say Charlemagne himself endowed his chapel with the original collection, while the rest were collected over time.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Others say all of the objects were collected over time, from such places as Jerusalem and Constantinople.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The location of this treasury has moved over time and was unknown until the 15th century when it was located in the Matthiaskapelle (St.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Matthew's Chapel) until 1873, when it was moved to the Karlskapelle (Charles' Chapel).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] From there it was moved to the Hungarian Chapel in 1881 and in 1931 to its present location next to the Allerseelenkapelle (Poor Souls' Chapel).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Only six of the original Carolingian objects have remained, and of those only three are left in Aachen: the Aachen Gospels, a diptych of Christ, and an early Byzantine silk.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The Coronation Gospels and a reliquary burse of St.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Stephen were moved to Vienna in 1798 and the Talisman of Charlemagne was given as a gift in 1804 to Josephine Bonaparte and subsequently to Rheims Cathedral.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] 210 documented pieces have been added to the treasury since its inception, typically to receive in return legitimisation of linkage to the heritage of Charlemagne.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The Lothar Cross, the Gospels of Otto III and multiple additional Byzantine silks were donated by Otto III.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Part of the Pala d'Oro and a covering for the Aachen Gospels were made of gold donated by Henry II.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Frederick Barbarossa donated the candelabrum that adorns the dome and also once "crowned" the Shrine of Charlemagne, which was placed underneath in 1215.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Charles IV donated a pair of reliquaries.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Louis XI gave, in 1475, the crown of Margaret of York, and, in 1481, another arm reliquary of Charlemagne.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Maximilian I and Charles V both gave numerous works of art by Hans von Reutlingen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Continuing the tradition, objects continued to be donated until the present, each indicative of the period of its gifting, with the last documented gift being a chalice from 1960 made by Ewald Mataré.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The Aachen Rathaus, (English: Aachen City Hall or Aachen Town Hall) dated from 1330, lies between two central squares, the *Markt* (marketplace) and the *Katschhof* (between city hall and cathedral).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The coronation hall is on the first floor of the building.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Inside one can find five frescoes by the Aachen artist Alfred Rethel which show legendary scenes from the life of Charlemagne, as well as Charlemagne's signature.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Also, precious replicas of the Imperial Regalia are kept here.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Since 2009, the city hall has been a station on the *Route Charlemagne*, a tour programme by which historical sights of Aachen are presented to visitors.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] At the city hall, a museum exhibition explains the history and art of the building and gives a sense of the historical coronation banquets that took place there.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] A portrait of Napoleon from 1807 by Louis-André-Gabriel Bouchet and one of his wife Joséphine from 1805 by Robert Lefèvre are viewable as part of the tour.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] As before, the city hall is the seat of the mayor of Aachen and of the city council, and annually the Charlemagne Prize is awarded there.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The *Grashaus*, a late medieval house at the *Fischmarkt*, is one of the oldest non-religious buildings in central Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] It hosted the city archive, and before that, the Grashaus was the city hall until the present building took over this function.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The *Elisenbrunnen* is one of the most famous sights of Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] It is a neo-classical hall covering one of the city's famous fountains.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] It is just a minute away from the cathedral.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Just a few steps in a south-easterly direction lies the 19th-century theatre.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Also of note are two remaining city gates, the *Ponttor* (Pont gate), 800 metres (1⁄2 mile) northwest of the cathedral, and the *Marschiertor* (marching gate), close to the central railway station.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] There are also a few parts of both medieval city walls left, most of them integrated into more recent buildings, but some others still visible.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] There are even five towers left, some of which are used for housing.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Michael's Church, Aachen was built as a church of the Aachen Jesuit Collegium in 1628.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] It is attributed to the Rhine mannerism, and a sample of a local Renaissance architecture.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The rich façade remained unfinished until 1891, when the architect Peter Friedrich Peters added to it.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The church is a Greek Orthodox church today, but the building is used also for concerts because of its good acoustics.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The synagogue in Aachen, which was destroyed on the Night of Broken Glass (Kristallnacht), 9 November 1938, was reinaugurated on 18 May 1995.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] One of the contributors to the reconstructions of the synagogue was Jürgen Linden, the Lord Mayor of Aachen from 1989 to 2009.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] There are numerous other notable churches and monasteries, a few remarkable 17th- and 18th-century buildings in the particular Baroque style typical of the region, a synagogue, a collection of statues and monuments, park areas, cemeteries, among others.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Among the museums in the town are the Suermondt-Ludwig Museum, which has a fine sculpture collection and the Aachen Museum of the International Press, which is dedicated to newspapers from the 16th century to the present.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] The area's industrial history is reflected in dozens of 19th- and early 20th-century manufacturing sites in the city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Aachen is the administrative centre for the coal-mining industries in neighbouring places to the northeast.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Products manufactured in Aachen include electrical goods, fine woolen textiles, foodstuffs (chocolate and candy), glass, machinery, rubber products, furniture, metal products.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Also in and around Aachen chemicals, plastics, cosmetics, and needles and pins are produced.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Though once a major player in Aachen's economy, today glassware and textile production make up only 10% of total manufacturing jobs in the city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] There have been a number of spin-offs from the university's IT technology department.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In June 2010, Achim Kampker, together with Günther Schuh, founded a small company to develop electric powered light utility vehicles; in August 2014, it was renamed StreetScooter GmbH.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] This started as a privately organised research initiative at the RWTH Aachen University, before becoming the independent company in Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] Kampker was also the founder and chairman of the European Network for Affordable and Sustainable Electromobility.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In May 2014, the company announced that the city of Aachen, the city council Aachen and the savings bank Aachen had ordered electric vehicles from the company.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In late 2014, approximately 70 employees were manufacturing 200 vehicles annually in the premises of the Waggonfabrik Talbot, the former Talbot/Bombardier plant in Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In December 2014 DHL Group purchased the StreetScooter company from Günther, operating it as a wholly owned subsidiary.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] In 2015, Günther founded a new electric vehicle company, e.GO Mobile, which started producing the e.GO Life electric passenger car and other vehicles in April 2019.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] By April 2016, StreetScooter announced that it would produce 2000 of its electric vans, branded the Work, in Aachen by the end of the year, and would be scaling up to manufacture approximately 10,000 Works annually, starting in 2017, also in Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p01] At the time, this target would make it the largest electric light utility vehicle manufacturer in Europe, surpassing Renault's smaller Kangoo Z.E.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] RWTH Aachen University, established as Polytechnicum in 1870, is one of Germany's Universities of Excellence with strong emphasis on technological research, especially for electrical and mechanical engineering, computer sciences, physics, and chemistry.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The university clinic attached to the RWTH, the Klinikum Aachen, is the biggest single-building hospital in Europe.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Over time, a host of software and computer industries have developed around the university.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] It also maintains a botanical garden (the Botanischer Garten Aachen).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] FH Aachen, Aachen University of Applied Sciences (AcUAS) was founded in 1971.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The AcUAS offers a classic engineering education in professions such as mechatronics, construction engineering, mechanical engineering or electrical engineering.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] German and international students are educated in more than 20 international or foreign-oriented programmes and can acquire German as well as international degrees (Bachelor/Master) or *Doppelabschlüsse* (double degrees).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Foreign students account for more than 21% of the student body.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The Katholische Hochschule Nordrhein-Westfalen – Abteilung Aachen (Catholic University of Applied Sciences Northrhine-Westphalia – Aachen department) offers its some 750 students a variety of degree programmes: social work, childhood education, nursing, and co-operative management.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] It also has the only programme of study in Germany especially designed for mothers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The Hochschule für Musik und Tanz Köln (Cologne University of Music) is one of the world's foremost performing arts schools and one of the largest music institutions for higher education in Europe with one of its three campuses in Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The Aachen campus substantially contributes to the Opera/Musical Theatre master's programme by collaborating with the Theater Aachen and the recently established musical theatre chair through the Rheinische Opernakademie.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The German Army's technical school *(Ausbildungszentrum Technik Landsysteme)* is located in Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The annual CHIO (short for the French term *Concours Hippique International Officiel*) is the biggest equestrian meeting of the world and among horsemen is considered to be as prestigious for equitation as the tournament of Wimbledon for tennis.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Aachen hosted the 2006 FEI World Equestrian Games.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The local football team Alemannia Aachen had a short run in Germany's first division, after its promotion in 2006.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] However, the team could not sustain its status and is now back in the third division.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The stadium "Tivoli", opened in 1928, served as the venue for the team's home games and was well known for its incomparable atmosphere throughout the whole of the second division.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Before the old stadium's demolition in 2011, it was used by amateurs, whilst the Bundesliga Club held its games in the new stadium "Neuer Tivoli" – meaning New Tivoli—a couple of metres down the road.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The building work for the stadium which has a capacity of 32,960, began in May 2008 and was completed by the beginning of 2009.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The Ladies in Black women's volleyball team (part of the "PTSV Aachen" sports club since 2013) has played in the first German volleyball league (DVL) since 2008.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] In June 2022, the local basketball club BG Aachen e.V. was promoted to the 1st regional league.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Aachen's railway station, the Hauptbahnhof (Central Station), was constructed in 1841 for the Cologne–Aachen railway line.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] In 1905, it was moved closer to the city centre.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] It serves main lines to Cologne, Mönchengladbach and Liège as well as branch lines to Heerlen, Alsdorf, Stolberg and Eschweiler.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] ICE high speed trains from Brussels via Cologne to Frankfurt am Main and Eurostar trains from Paris to Cologne also stop at Aachen Central Station.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Four RE lines and two RB lines connect Aachen with the Ruhrgebiet, Mönchengladbach, Spa (Belgium), Düsseldorf and the Siegerland.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The *Euregiobahn*, a regional railway system, reaches several minor cities in the Aachen region.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] There are four smaller stations in Aachen: *Aachen West*, *Aachen Schanz*, *Aachen-Rothe Erde* and *Eilendorf*.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Aachen West has gained in importance with the expansion of RWTH Aachen University.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] There are two stations for intercity bus services in Aachen: Aachen West station, in the north-west of the city, and Aachen Wilmersdorfer Straße, in the north-east.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The first horse tram line in Aachen opened in December 1880.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] After electrification in 1895, it attained a maximum length of 213.5 kilometres (132+5⁄8 miles) in 1915, thus becoming the fourth-longest tram network in Germany.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Many tram lines extended to the surrounding towns of Herzogenrath, Stolberg, Alsdorf as well as the Belgian and Dutch communes of Vaals, Kelmis (then *Altenberg*) and Eupen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The Aachen tram system was linked with the Belgian national interurban tram system.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Like many tram systems in Western Europe, the Aachen tram suffered from poorly maintained infrastructure and was so deemed unnecessary and disrupting for car drivers by local politics.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] On 28 September 1974, the last line 15 (Vaals–Brand) operated for one last day and was then replaced by buses.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] A proposal to reinstate a tram/light rail system under the name *Campusbahn* was dropped after a referendum.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Today, the ASEAG (*Aachener Straßenbahn und Energieversorgungs-AG*, literally "Aachen Tram and Power Supply Company") operates a 1,240.8-kilometre-long (771 mi) bus network with 68 bus routes.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Because of the location at the border, many bus routes extend to Belgium and the Netherlands.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Lines 14 to Eupen, Belgium and 44 to Heerlen, Netherlands are jointly operated with Transport en Commun and Veolia Transport Nederland, respectively.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] ASEAG is one of the main participants in the Aachener Verkehrsverbund (AVV), a tariff association in the region.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Along with ASEAG, city bus routes of Aachen are served by private contractors such as Sadar, Taeter, Schlömer, or DB Regio Bus.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Line 350, which runs from Maastricht, also enters Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Aachen is connected to the Autobahn A4 (west-east), A44 (north-south) and A544 (a smaller motorway from the A4 to the *Europaplatz* near the city centre).
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] There are plans to eliminate traffic jams at the Aachen road interchange.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Maastricht Aachen Airport (IATA: **MST**, ICAO: **EHBK**) is the main airport of Aachen and Maastricht.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] It is located around 15 nautical miles (28 kilometres; 17 miles) northwest of Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] There is a shuttle-service between Aachen and the airport.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] However, the airport only offers limited European destinations.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The nearest major international airports are Cologne Bonn Airport, located 88 km (55 mi) east and Düsseldorf Airport, located 97.1 km (60 mi) northeast of Aachen.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Recreational aviation is served by the (formerly military) Aachen Merzbrück Airfield.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Since 1950, a committee of Aachen citizens annually awards the Charlemagne Prize (German: *Karlspreis*) to personalities of outstanding service to the unification of Europe.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] It is traditionally awarded on Ascension Day at the City Hall.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] In 2016, the Charlemagne Award was awarded to Pope Francis.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] In 2004, Pope John Paul II's efforts to unite Europe were honoured with an "Extraordinary Charlemagne Medal", which was awarded for the only time ever.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] Aix is the destination in Robert Browning's poem "How They Brought the Good News from Ghent to Aix", which was published in *Dramatic Romances and Lyrics*, 1845.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachen-p02] The poem is a first-person narrative told, in breathless galloping meter, by one of three riders; an urgent midnight errand to deliver "the news which alone could save Aix from her fate".
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachener-zeitung] The AZ was founded in 1946 as ***Aachener Volkszeitung*** (AVZ) by Jakob Schmitz, Josef Hofmann, Albert Maas and Johannes Ernst, first printed on 22 February 1946.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachener-zeitung] It was the first free paper published by Germans after World War II.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachener-zeitung] The paper was renamed *Aachener Zeitung* on 6 March 1996.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachener-zeitung] The paper was printed initially only two or three times a week, but daily every working day from 1 September 1949; it is sold mainly by subscription and the circulation is about 112,000 copies.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachener-zeitung] The paper supplies news from around the world, but with a focus on the region, its politics, economy, culture, sports and weather, for readers in Aachen, Eschweiler, Geilenkirchen and Jülich.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachener-zeitung] Bernd Mathieu is the current editor-in-chief, of the Aachener Zeitung from 1995 and of the Aachener Nachrichten from 2003.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachener-zeitung] The concept of two newspapers in one *Redaktion* was then new for Germany.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachener-zeitung] Mathieu is a lecturer at the Aachen University of Applied Sciences for *Digital Business* in media and communications studies.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachener-zeitung] He is a member of the jury of the journalism prize Theodor Wolff Prize.
[src:aachener-zeitung/aachener-zeitung] Mathieu initiated online news service, namely a digital daily evening news "AmAbend" with photo galleries and videos, provided from 7 pm, in addition to the printed papers which include weekly specials on Wednesdays and Sundays.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] The ***Belfast Telegraph*** is a daily newspaper published in Belfast, Northern Ireland.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] First published in 1870 as the ***Belfast Evening Telegraph***, as 2020 its editor was Eoin Brannigan.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] Reflecting its unionist tradition, the paper has historically been "favoured by the Protestant population", while also being read within Catholic nationalist communities in Northern Ireland.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] Owned by Independent News and Media (INM), a Dublin-based media company, from 2000, the INM group of newspapers was acquired by Mediahuis Ireland in 2019.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] Mediahuis Ireland also publishes the *Irish Independent*, the *Sunday Independent* and various other newspapers and magazines in Ireland.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] In 2012, the newspaper moved to being exclusively a morning only publication and, as of 2024, no longer revealed circulation figures (sales figures), but rather releases the number of readers "reached" daily.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] In 2024, Mediahuis stated that the *Belfast Telegraph* was "reaching 143,311 readers" per day.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] The newspaper was first published as the *Belfast Evening Telegraph* on 1 September 1870 by brothers William and George Baird.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] Its first edition cost half a penny and ran to four pages covering the Franco-Prussian War and local news.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] The evening edition of the newspaper was originally called the "Sixth Late", and "Sixth Late Tele" was a familiar cry made by vendors in Belfast city centre in the past.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] Local editions were published for distribution to Enniskillen, Dundalk, Newry, and Derry.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] Its competitors are *The News Letter* and *The Irish News*, and local editions of London-based red tops also compete in this market, in some cases selling at a cheaper price than the "Tele".
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] Sometimes described as having "unionist leanings", and operating an editorial policy supportive of "moderate unionism", the *Belfast Telegraph* was bought by the Dublin-based Independent News & Media (INM) group in March 2000.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] It was INM's only print title outside of the Republic of Ireland.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] The *Belfast Telegraph* was entirely broadsheet until 19 February 2005, when the Saturday morning edition was introduced and all Saturday editions were converted to compact.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] The weekday morning compact edition was launched on 22 March 2005.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] In 2015, the newspaper launched the magazine supplement *Family Life*.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] The INM group of newspapers, including the *Belfast Telegraph*, was acquired by Mediahuis Ireland (in turn owned by the Belgian company Mediahuis Partners NV) in 2019.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] As of 2026, the paper was publishing two editions daily, *Belfast Telegraph* final edition and the *North West Telegraph* which is distributed in Derry.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] The *Belfast Telegraph* was named as Best UK Regional Newspaper of the Year 2012 by the Society of Editors Regional Press Awards.
[src:aachener-zeitung/belfast-telegraph] Reflecting a decline in newspaper sales generally, circulation of the *Belfast Telegraph* has declined as of the early 21st century, from 109,571 for the period July to December 2002, to 31,340 for the same period in 2019.
[src:aachener-zeitung/bray-people] Below is a list of newspapers published in Ireland.
[src:aachener-zeitung/contacto-luxembourg] The paper caters to the large Lusophone community in Luxembourg, primarily Portuguese and Cape Verdean Luxembourgers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/dagblad-van-het-noorden] The ***Dagblad van het Noorden*** (Dutch pronunciation: [ˈdɑɣblɑt fɑn ət ˈnoːrdə(n)]; English: Daily Newspaper of the North), abbreviated as ***DvhN***, is a Dutch regional daily newspaper that is published and circulated in the provinces of Groningen and Drenthe in the northeastern Netherlands.
[src:aachener-zeitung/dagblad-van-het-noorden] Erik Wijnholds has been editor-in-chief since 2017.
[src:aachener-zeitung/dagblad-van-het-noorden] It had a circulation of 96,515 copies in 2015.
[src:aachener-zeitung/dagblad-van-het-noorden] The *Dagblad van het Noorden* is a merger of the *Nieuwsblad van het Noorden* (founded in 1888), the *Groninger Dagblad* (founded by merger in 1992) and the *Drentse Courant* (founded by merger in 1991).
[src:aachener-zeitung/dagblad-van-het-noorden] Its first edition was published on 2 April 2002.
[src:aachener-zeitung/dagblad-van-het-noorden] Jan Bonjer, who had been the editor-in-chief of the *Drentse Courant*, was the first editor-in-chief from 2002 to 2003.
[src:aachener-zeitung/dagblad-van-het-noorden] Pieter Sijpersma was editor-in-chief from 2004 till 2017, when he was succeeded by Erik Wijnholds.
[src:aachener-zeitung/dagblad-van-het-noorden] The newspaper circulation started around 180,000 subscribers in 2002 and diminished to less than 100,000 subscribers in 2015.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] A **newspaper** is a periodical publication containing written information about current events and is often typed in black ink with a white or gray background.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Newspapers can cover a wide variety of fields such as politics, business, sports, art, science, and religions.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] They often include materials such as opinion columns, weather forecasts, reviews of local services, obituaries, birth notices, crosswords, sudoku puzzles, editorial cartoons, comic strips, and advice columns.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Most newspapers are businesses, and they pay their expenses with a mixture of subscription revenue, newsstand sales, and advertising revenue.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The journalism organizations that publish newspapers are themselves often metonymically called newspapers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Newspapers have traditionally been published in print (usually on cheap, low-grade paper called newsprint).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] However, today most newspapers are also published on websites as online newspapers, and some have even abandoned their print versions entirely.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Newspapers developed in the 17th century as information sheets for merchants.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] By the early 19th century, many cities in Europe, as well as North and South America, published newspapers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Some newspapers with high editorial independence, high journalism quality, and large circulation are viewed as newspapers of record.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] With the popularity of the Internet, many newspapers are now digital, with their news presented online as the main medium that most of the readers use, with the print edition being secondary (for the minority of customers that choose to pay for it) or, in some cases, retired.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The decline of newspapers in the early 21st century was at first largely interpreted as a mere print-versus-digital contest in which digital beats print.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The reality is different and multivariate, as newspapers now routinely have online presence; anyone willing to subscribe can read them digitally online.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Factors such as classified ads no longer being a large revenue center (because of other ways to buy and sell online) and ad impressions now being dispersed across many media are inputs.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Newspapers are typically published daily or weekly.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] News magazines are also weekly, but they have a magazine format.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] General-interest newspapers typically publish news articles and feature articles on national and international news as well as local news.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The news includes political events and politicians.", business and finance, crime, weather, and natural disasters; health and medicine, science, and computers and technology; sports; and entertainment, society, food and cooking, clothing and home fashion, and the arts.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Usually, the paper is divided into sections for each of those major groupings (labelled A, B, C, and so on, with pagination prefixes yielding page numbers A1-A20, B1-B20, C1-C20, and so on).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Papers also include articles that have no byline; these articles are written by staff writers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] A wide variety of material has been published in newspapers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Newspapers have classified ad sections where people and businesses can buy small advertisements to sell goods or services; as of 2013, an increase in Internet websites for selling goods, such as Craigslist and eBay has led to significantly less classified ad sales for newspapers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Most newspapers are businesses, and they pay their expenses with a mixture of subscription revenue, newsstand sales, and advertising revenue (other businesses or individuals pay to place advertisements in the pages, including display ads, classified ads, and their online equivalents).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Some newspapers are government-run or at least government-funded; their reliance on advertising revenue and profitability is less critical to their survival.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The editorial independence of a newspaper is thus always subject to the interests of someone, whether owners, advertisers or a government.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Many newspapers, besides employing journalists on their own payrolls, also subscribe to news agencies (wire services) (such as the Associated Press, Reuters, or Agence France-Presse), which employ journalists to find, assemble, and report the news, then sell the content to the various newspapers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] This is a way to avoid duplicating the expense of reporting from around the world. c.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] 2005, there were approximately 6,580 daily newspaper titles in the world selling 395 million print copies a day (in the U.S., 1,450 titles selling 55 million copies).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The late 2000s–early 2010s global recession, combined with the rapid growth of free web-based alternatives, has helped cause a decline in advertising and circulation, as many papers had to retrench operations to stanch the losses.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Worldwide annual revenue approached $100 billion in 2005–7, then plunged during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Revenue in 2016 fell to only $53 billion, hurting every major publisher as their efforts to gain online income fell far short of the goal.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The decline in advertising revenues affected both the print and online media as well as all other mediums; print advertising was once lucrative but has greatly declined, and the prices of online advertising are often lower than those of their print precursors.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Besides remodelling advertising, the internet (especially the web) has also challenged the business models of the print-only era by crowdsourcing both publishing in general (sharing information with others) and, more specifically, journalism (the work of finding, assembling, and reporting the news).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Besides, the rise of news aggregators, which bundle linked articles from many online newspapers and other sources, influences the flow of web traffic.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Increasing paywalling of online newspapers may be counteracting those effects.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The oldest newspaper still published is the *Ordinari Post Tijdender*, which was established in Stockholm in 1645.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Manuscript newsletters circulated by the 15th century in Europe, and the Fugger banking family systematised the distribution of information.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first mechanical, movable type printing that allowed the mass production of printed material was invented by Johann Gutenberg around 1450.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the 50 years after Gutenberg started printing, an estimated 500,000 books were in circulation, printed on about 1,000 presses across the continent.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Gutenberg's invention was a simple device, but it launched a revolution marked by repeated advances in technology and, as a result, a popularization of the ideals of liberty and freedom of information exchange.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The emergence of the new media in the 17th century has to be seen in close connection with the spread of the printing press from which the publishing press derives its name.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The German-language *Relation aller Fürnemmen und gedenckwürdigen Historien*, printed from 1605 onwards by Johann Carolus in Strasbourg in the Holy Roman Empire of the German Nation, is often recognized as the first newspaper.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The second newspaper, the German *Avisa*, was published from 1609 in Wolfenbüttel.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Both newspapers distinguished themselves from other printed material by being published on a regular basis.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] They reported on a variety of current events to a broad public audience.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] For distribution, regular, printed news summaries leveraged off the "extension of the system of 'posts' whereby the imperial couriers were permitted to carry letters for individuals.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The beginnings of that extension of the system cannot be documented before the middle of the sixteenth century, and occur first in Austria and Germany.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] From which it followed that the earliest dated, and numbered, publication of news [occurred] in Central and West Europe." Within a few decades, newspapers could be found in all the major cities of Europe, from Venice to London.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The Dutch *Courante uyt Italien, Duytslandt, &c.* ("Courant from Italy, Germany, etc.") of 1618 was the first to appear in folio- rather than quarto-size.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Amsterdam, a center of world trade, quickly became home to newspapers in many languages, often before they were published in their own country.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first English-language newspaper, *Corrant out of Italy, Germany, etc.*, was published in Amsterdam in 1620.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the same year, the Antwerp periodial *Nieuwe Tijdinghen* was published by Abraham Verhoeven.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In 1621, *Corante, or weekely newes from Italy, Germany, Hungary, Poland, Bohemia, France and the Low Countreys* was published in England by an "N.B." (generally thought to be either Nathaniel Butter or Nicholas Bourne) and Thomas Archer.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first newspaper in France was published in 1631, *La Gazette* (originally published as *Gazette de France*).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first newspaper in Italy, in accordance with the oldest issue still preserved, was *Di Genova* published in 1639 in Genoa.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first newspaper in Portugal, *A Gazeta da Restauração*, was published in 1641 in Lisbon.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first Spanish newspaper, Gaceta de Madrid, was published in 1661.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In Boston in 1690, Benjamin Harris published *Publick Occurrences Both Forreign and Domestick*.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] This is considered the first newspaper in the American colonies even though only one edition was published before the paper was suppressed by the government.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In 1704, the governor allowed *The Boston News-Letter* to be published and it became the first continuously published newspaper in the colonies.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Soon after, weekly papers began being published in New York and Philadelphia.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] These early newspapers followed the British format and were usually four pages long.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] They mostly carried news from Britain and content depended on the editor's interests.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In 1783, the *Pennsylvania Evening Post* became the first American daily.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In 1752, John Bushell published the *Halifax Gazette*, which claims to be "Canada's first newspaper".
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] It is currently published as an English-language weekly from its offices at 1040 Belvédère, suite 218, Quebec City, Quebec, Canada.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In 1808, the *Gazeta do Rio de Janeiro* had its first edition, printed in devices brought from England, publishing news favourable for the government of the United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves since it was produced by the official press service of the Portuguese crown.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first newspaper in Peru was *El Peruano*, established in October 1825 and still published today, but with several name changes.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] During the Tang dynasty in China (618–906), the *Kaiyuan Za Bao* published the government news; it was block-printed onto paper.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] It is sometimes considered one of the earliest newspapers to be published.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first recorded attempt to found a newspaper of the modern type in South Asia was by William Bolts, a Dutchman in the employ of the British East India Company in September 1768 in Calcutta.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] However, before he could begin his newspaper, he was deported back to Europe.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In 1780 the first newsprint from this region, *Hicky's Bengal Gazette*, was published by an Irishman, James Augustus Hicky.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] He used it as a means to criticize the British rule through journalism.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The *Jobo*, discussed in the Annals of the Joseon Dynasty, was published in 1577 by King Seonjo's ministers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] As the King had not given permission to print the news bulletins, *Jobo* was discontinued, and 30 ministers were sentenced "to a severe punishment".
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] It was printed daily, and covered a range of topics, including weather, constellations, and current affairs.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In 2017, a Korean monk claimed to have discovered an extant copy of the *Jobo*.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The history of Middle Eastern newspapers goes back to the 19th century.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Many editors were not only journalists but also writers, philosophers and politicians.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] With unofficial journals, these intellectuals encouraged public discourse on politics in the Ottoman and Persian Empires.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Literary works of all genres were serialized and published in the press as well.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first newspapers in the Ottoman Empire were owned by foreigners living there who wanted to make propaganda about the Western world.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The earliest was printed in 1795 by the Palais de France in Pera.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Indigenous Middle Eastern journalism started in 1828, when Muhammad Ali, Khedive of Egypt, ordered the local establishment of the gazette *Vekâyi-i Mısriyye* (*Egyptian Affairs*).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] It was first paper written in Ottoman Turkish and Arabic on opposite pages, and later in Arabic only, under the title "*Al-Waqāʾiʿ al-Miṣriyya*".
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first non-official Turkish newspaper, *Ceride-i Havadis* (Register of Events), was published by an Englishman, William Churchill, in 1840.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first private newspaper to be published by Turkish journalists, *Tercüman-ı Ahvâl* (Interpreter of Events), was founded by İbrahim Şinasi and Agah Efendi and issued in 1860.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first newspaper in Iran, *Kaghaz-e Akhbar* (The Newspaper), was created for the government by Mirza Saleh Shirazi in 1837.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The first journals in the Arabian Peninsula appeared in Hijaz, once it had become independent of Ottoman rule, towards the end of World War I.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] One of the earliest women to sign her articles in the Arab press was the female medical practitioner Galila Tamarhan, who contributed articles to a medical magazine called "*Ya'asub al-Tib*" (Leader in Medicine) in the 1860s.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] By the early 19th century, many cities in Europe, as well as North and South America, published newspaper-type publications though not all of them developed in the same way; content was vastly shaped by regional and cultural preferences.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Advances in printing technology related to the Industrial Revolution enabled newspapers to become an even more widely circulated means of communication, as new printing technologies made printing less expensive and more efficient.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In 1814, *The Times* (London) acquired a printing press capable of making 1,100 impressions per hour.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Soon, this press was adapted to print on both sides of a page at once.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] This innovation made newspapers cheaper and thus available to a larger part of the population.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In 1830, the first inexpensive "penny press" newspaper came to the market: Lynde M.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Penny press papers cost about one sixth the price of other newspapers and appealed to a wider audience, including less educated and lower-income people.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In France, Émile de Girardin started *La Presse* in 1836, introducing cheap, advertising-supported dailies to France.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In 1848, August Zang, an Austrian who knew Girardin in Paris, returned to Vienna to introduce the same methods with *Die Presse* (which was named for and frankly copied Girardin's publication).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] More specialist still are some weekly newspapers, usually free and distributed within limited regional areas; these may serve communities as specific as certain immigrant populations, the local gay community or indie rock enthusiasts within a city or region.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] A **daily newspaper** is printed every day, sometimes with the exception of Sundays and occasionally Saturdays (and some major holidays).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Saturday and, where they exist, Sunday editions of daily newspapers tend to be larger, include more specialized sections (e.g., on arts, films, entertainment) and advertising inserts, and cost more.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Typically, the majority of these newspapers' staff members work Monday to Friday, so the Sunday and Monday editions largely depend on content made in advance or content that is syndicated.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Most daily newspapers are sold in the morning.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Afternoon or evening papers, once common but now scarce, are aimed more at commuters and office workers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In practice (though this may vary according to country), a morning newspaper is available in early editions from before midnight on the night before its cover date, further editions being printed and distributed during the night.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The later editions can include breaking news which was first revealed that day, after the morning edition was already printed.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Previews of tomorrow's newspapers are often a feature of late night news programs, such as *Newsnight* in the United Kingdom.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In 1650, the first daily newspaper appeared, *Einkommende Zeitung*, published by Timotheus Ritzsch in Leipzig, Germany.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the United Kingdom and some other Commonwealth countries, unlike most other countries, daily newspapers do not publish on Sundays.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In some countries daily newspapers are not published on Christmas Day, but weekly newspapers would change their day e.g.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Sunday newspapers are published on Saturday 24 December, Christmas Eve when Christmas Day falls on Sunday.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Some newspapers are published two times a week and are known as semi-weekly publications.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] As the name suggests, a **triweekly** publishes three times a week.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The *Meridian Star* is an example of such a publication.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Weekly newspapers are published once a week, and tend to be smaller than daily papers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Some publications are published, for example, fortnightly (or biweekly in American parlance).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] They may have a change from normal weekly day of the week during the Christmas period depending the day of the week Christmas Day is falling on.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] A **local newspaper** serves a region such as a city, or part of a large city.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Almost every market has one or two newspapers that dominate the area.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Large metropolitan newspapers often have large distribution networks, and can be found outside their normal area, sometimes widely, sometimes from fewer sources.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Most nations have at least one newspaper that circulates throughout the whole country: a **national newspaper**.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Some national newspapers, such as the *Financial Times* and *The Wall Street Journal*, are specialised (in these examples, on financial matters).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] There are many national newspapers in the United Kingdom, but only a few in the United States and Canada.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In Canada, *The Globe and Mail* is sold throughout the country.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the United States, in addition to national newspapers as such, *The New York Times* is available throughout the country.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] There is also a small group of newspapers which may be characterized as **international newspapers**.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Some, such as *The New York Times International Edition*, (formerly The International Herald Tribune) have always had that focus, while others are repackaged national newspapers or "international editions" of national or large metropolitan newspapers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In some cases, articles that might not interest the wider range of readers are omitted from international editions; in others, of interest to expatriates, significant national news is retained.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] As English became the international language of business and technology, many newspapers formerly published only in non-English languages have also developed English-language editions.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In places as varied as Jerusalem and Mumbai, newspapers are printed for a local and international English-speaking public, and for tourists.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The advent of the Internet has also allowed non-English-language newspapers to put out a scaled-down English version to give their newspaper a global outreach.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Similarly, in many countries with a large foreign-language-speaking population or many tourists, newspapers in languages other than the national language are both published locally and imported.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] For example, newspapers and magazines from many countries, and locally published newspapers in many languages, are ready to be found on news-stands in central London.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the US state of Florida, so many tourists from the French-speaking Canadian province of Quebec visit for long stays during the winter ("snowbirds") that some newsstands and stores sell French-language newspapers such as *Le Droit*.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] General newspapers cover all topics, with different emphasis.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] While at least mentioning all topics, some might have good coverage of international events of importance; others might concentrate more on national or local entertainment or sports.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Specialised newspapers might concentrate more specifically on, for example, financial matters.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] There are publications covering exclusively sports, or certain sports, horse-racing, theatre, and so on, although they may no longer be called newspapers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] For centuries newspapers were printed on paper and supplied physically to readers either by the local distribution or in some cases by mail, for example for British expatriates living in India or Hong Kong who subscribed to British newspapers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Newspapers can be delivered to subscribers homes and/or businesses by a paper's own delivery people, sent via the mail, sold at newsstands, grocery stores, and convenience stores, and delivered to libraries and bookstores.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Newspaper organizations need a large distribution system to deliver their papers to these different distributors, which typically involves delivery trucks and delivery people.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In recent years, newspapers and other media have adapted to the changing technology environment by starting to offer online editions to cater to the needs of the public.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the future, the trend towards more electronic delivery of the news will continue with more emphasis on the Internet, social media and other electronic delivery methods.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] However, while the method of delivery is changing, the newspaper and the industry still have a niche in the world.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] As of 2007, virtually all major printed newspapers produced online editions distributed over the Internet, which, depending on the country, may be regulated by journalism organizations such as the Press Complaints Commission in the UK.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Since 2005 in the UK more than 200 regional newspapers have closed down resulting in a 50% decline in the number of regional journalists.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] A 2016 study by King's College, London, found that the towns that lost their local newspapers receded from democratic values and experienced the loss of public faith in the authorities.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] A new trend in newspaper publishing is the introduction of personalization through on-demand printing technologies or with online news aggregator websites like Google news.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Customized newspapers allow the reader to create their individual newspaper through the selection of individual pages from multiple publications.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] This "Best of" approach allows revival of the print-based model and opens up a new distribution channel to increase coverage beneath the usual boundaries of distribution.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Customized newspapers online have been offered by MyYahoo, I-Google, CRAYON, ICurrent.com, Kibboko.com, Twitter. times and many others.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] With these online newspapers, the reader can select how much of each section (politics, sports, arts, etc.) they wish to see in their news.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the U.S., the overall manager or chief executive of the newspaper is the publisher.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In small newspapers, the owner of the publication (or the largest shareholder in the corporation that owns the publication) is usually the publisher.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Most newspapers have four main departments devoted to publishing the newspaper itself—editorial, production/printing, circulation, and advertising, although they are frequently referred to by a variety of other names.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Most papers also have the non-newspaper-specific departments found in other businesses of comparable size, such as accounting, marketing, human resources, and IT.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Throughout the English-speaking world, the person who selects the content for the newspaper is usually referred to as the editor.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Variations on this title such as editor-in-chief, executive editor, and so on are common.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] For small newspapers, a single editor may be responsible for all content areas.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] At large newspapers, the most senior editor is in overall charge of the publication, while less senior editors may each focus on one subject area, such as local news or sports.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] These divisions are called news bureaus or "desks", and each is supervised by a designated editor.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Most newspaper editors copy edit the stories for their part of the newspaper, but they may share their workload with proofreaders and fact checkers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Reporters are journalists who primarily report facts that they have gathered, and those who write longer, less news-oriented articles may be called feature writers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Photographers and graphic artists provide images and illustrations to support articles.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Journalists often specialize in a subject area, called a beat, such as sports, religion, or science.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Columnists are journalists who write regular articles recounting their personal opinions and experiences.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Printers and press operators physically print the newspaper.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] If the newspaper offers information online, webmasters and web designers may be employed to upload stories to the newspaper's website.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The staff of the circulation department liaise with retailers who sell the newspaper; sell subscriptions; and supervise distribution of the printed newspapers through the mail, by newspaper carriers, at retailers, and through vending machines.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Free newspapers do not sell subscriptions, but they still have a circulation department responsible for distributing the newspapers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Sales staff in the advertising department not only sell ad space to clients such as local businesses, but also help clients design and plan their advertising campaigns.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Other members of the advertising department may include graphic designers, who design ads according to the customers' specifications and the department's policies.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In an advertising-free newspaper, there is no advertising department.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Newspapers often refine distribution of ads and news through zoning and editioning.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Zoning occurs when advertising and editorial content change to reflect the location to which the product is delivered.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The editorial content often may change merely to reflect changes in advertising—the quantity and layout of which affects the space available for editorial—or may contain region-specific news.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In rare instances, the advertising may not change from one zone to another, but there will be different region-specific editorial content.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] As the content can vary widely, zoned editions are often produced in parallel.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Editioning occurs in the main sections as news is updated throughout the night.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The advertising is usually the same in each edition (with the exception of zoned regionals, in which it is often the 'B' section of local news that undergoes advertising changes).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] As each edition represents the latest news available for the next press run, these editions are produced linearly, with one completed edition being copied and updated for the next edition.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The previous edition is always copied to maintain a Newspaper of Record and to fall back on if a quick correction is needed for the press.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] For example, both *The New York Times* and *The Wall Street Journal* offer a regional edition, printed through a local contractor, and featuring locale specific content.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The Journal's global advertising rate card provides a good example of editioning.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The Brazilian Vossa Senhoria claims to be the smallest newspaper in the world, measuring in at 1.4 in. x 1 in (3.5 cm x 2.5 cm).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Newspapers are usually printed on cheap, off-white paper known as newsprint.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Since the 1980s, the newspaper industry has largely moved away from lower-quality letterpress printing to higher-quality, four-color process, offset printing.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In addition, desktop computers, word processing software, graphics software, digital cameras and digital prepress and typesetting technologies have revolutionized the newspaper production process.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] These technologies have enabled newspapers to publish color photographs and graphics, as well as innovative layouts and better design.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] To help their titles stand out on newsstands, some newspapers are printed on coloured newsprint.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] For example, the *Financial Times* is printed on a distinctive salmon pink paper, and Sheffield's weekly sports publication derives its name, the *Green 'Un*, from the traditional colour of its paper.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The Italian sports newspaper *La Gazzetta dello Sport* is also printed on pink paper while *L'Équipe* (formerly *L'Auto*) is printed on yellow paper.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Both the latter promoted major cycling races and their newsprint colours were reflected in the colours of the jerseys used to denote the race leader; for example the leader in the Giro d'Italia wears a pink jersey.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The number of copies distributed, either on an average day or on particular days (typically Sunday), is called the newspaper's circulation and is one of the principal factors used to set advertising rates.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Circulation is not necessarily the same as copies sold, since some copies or newspapers are distributed without cost.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Readership figures may be higher than circulation figures, because many copies are read by more than one person, although this is offset by the number of copies distributed but not read (especially for those distributed free).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the United States, the Alliance for Audited Media maintains historical and current data on average circulation of daily and weekly newspapers and other periodicals.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] According to the *Guinness Book of Records*, the daily circulation of the Soviet newspaper *Trud* exceeded 21,500,000 in 1990, while the Soviet weekly *Argumenty i Fakty* boasted a circulation of 33,500,000 in 1991.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] According to United Nations data from 1995 Japan has three daily papers—the *Yomiuri Shimbun* with circulations well above 5.5 million.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Germany's *Bild*, with a circulation of 1.15 million, was the only other paper in that category.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the United Kingdom, *The Sun* is the top seller, with around 1.2 million copies distributed daily.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the U.S., *The Wall Street Journal* has a daily circulation of approximately 2.02 million, making it the most widely distributed paper in the country.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] While paid readership of print newspapers has been steadily declining in the developed OECD nations, it has been rising in the chief developing nations (Brazil, India, Indonesia, China and South Africa), whose paid daily circulation exceeded those of the developed nations for the first time in 2008.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In India, *The Times of India* is the largest-circulation English newspaper, with 3.14 million copies daily.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] According to the 2009 Indian Readership Survey, the *Dainik Jagran* is the most-read, local-language (Hindi) newspaper, with 55.7 million readers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] According to Tom Standage of *The Economist*, India currently has daily newspaper circulation of 110 million copies.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] A common measure of a newspaper's health is market penetration, expressed as a percentage of households that receive a copy of the newspaper against the total number of households in the paper's market area.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the 1920s, on a national basis in the U.S., daily newspapers achieved market penetration of 123 percent (meaning the average U.S. household received 1.23 newspapers).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] As other media began to compete with newspapers, and as printing became easier and less expensive giving rise to a greater diversity of publications, market penetration began to decline.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] It was not until the early 1970s, however, that market penetration dipped below 100 percent.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] By 2000, it was 53 percent and still falling.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Many paid-for newspapers offer a variety of subscription plans.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] For example, someone might want only a Sunday paper, or perhaps only Sunday and Saturday, or maybe only a workweek subscription, or perhaps a daily subscription.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Most newspapers provide some or all of their content on the Internet, either at no cost or for a fee.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In some cases, free access is available only for a matter of days or weeks, or for a certain number of viewed articles, after which readers must register and provide personal data.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In other cases, free archives are provided.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] A newspaper typically generates 70–80% of its revenue from advertising, and the remainder from sales and subscriptions.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The portion of the newspaper that is not advertising is called *editorial content*, *editorial matter*, or simply *editorial*, although the last term is also used to refer specifically to those articles in which the newspaper and its guest writers express their opinions.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] (This distinction, however, developed over time – early publishers like Girardin (France) and Zang (Austria) did not always distinguish paid items from editorial content.).
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The business model of having advertising subsidize the cost of printing and distributing newspapers (and, it is always hoped, the making of a profit) rather than having subscribers cover the full cost was first done, it seems, in 1833 by *The Sun*, a daily paper that was published in New York City.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Rather than charging 6 cents per copy, the price of a typical New York daily at the time, they charged 1-cent, and depended on advertising to make up the difference.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Newspapers in countries with easy access to the web have been hurt by the decline of many traditional advertisers.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Department stores and supermarkets could be relied upon in the past to buy pages of newspaper advertisements, but due to industry consolidation are much less likely to do so now.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Additionally, newspapers are seeing traditional advertisers shift to new media platforms.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The classified category is shifting to sites including Craigslist, employment websites, and auto sites.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] National advertisers are shifting to many types of digital content including websites, rich media platforms, and mobile.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In recent years, the advertorial emerged.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Advertorials are most commonly recognized as an opposite-editorial which third parties pay a fee to have included in the paper.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Advertorials commonly advertise new products or techniques, such as a new design for golf equipment, a new form of laser surgery, or weight-loss drugs.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The tone is usually closer to that of a press release than of an objective news story.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Such articles are often clearly distinguished from editorial content through either the design and layout of the page or with a label declaring the article as an advertisement.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] However, there has been growing concern over the blurring of the line between editorial and advertorial content.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Since newspapers began as a journal (record of current events), the profession involved in the making of newspapers began to be called *journalism*.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the yellow journalism era of the 19th century, many newspapers in the United States relied on sensational stories that were meant to anger or excite the public, rather than to inform.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The restrained style of reporting that relies on fact checking and accuracy regained popularity around World War II.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Criticism of journalism is varied and sometimes vehement.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Credibility is questioned because of anonymous sources; errors in facts, spelling, and grammar; real or perceived bias; and scandals involving plagiarism and fabrication.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the past, newspapers have often been owned by so-called press barons, and were used for gaining a political voice.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Newspapers have, in the modern world, played an important role in the exercise of freedom of expression.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Whistle-blowers, and those who "leak" stories of corruption in political circles often choose to inform newspapers before other mediums of communication, relying on the perceived willingness of newspaper editors to expose the secrets and lies of those who would rather cover them.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] However, there have been many circumstances of the political autonomy of newspapers being curtailed.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Recent research has examined the effects of a newspaper's closing on the reelection of incumbents, voter turnout, and campaign spending.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Opinions of other writers and readers are expressed in the *op-ed* ("opposite the editorial page") and *letters to the editors* sections of the paper.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Some ways newspapers have tried to improve their credibility are: appointing ombudsmen, developing ethics policies and training, using more stringent corrections policies, communicating their processes and rationale with readers, and asking sources to review articles after publication.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] By the late 1990s, the availability of news via 24-hour television channels and the subsequent availability of online journalism posed an ongoing challenge to the business model of most newspapers in developed countries.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Paid newspaper circulation has declined, while advertising revenue—the bulk of most newspapers' income—has been shifting from print to social media and news websites, resulting in a general decline.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] One of the challenges is that a number of online news websites are free to access.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Other online news sites have a paywall and require paid subscription for access.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In less-developed countries, cheaper printing and distribution, increased literacy, a growing middle class, and other factors have compensated for the emergence of electronic media, and newspaper circulation continues to grow.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In April 1995, *The American Reporter* became the first daily Internet-based newspaper with its own paid reporters and original content.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The future of newspapers in countries with high levels of Internet access has been widely debated as the industry has faced down soaring newsprint prices, slumping ad sales, the loss of much classified advertising, and precipitous drops in circulation.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Since the late-1990s, the number of newspapers slated for closure, bankruptcy, or severe cutbacks has risen—especially in the United States, where the industry has shed a fifth of its journalists since 2001.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] A June 2022 report estimated that 2 newspapers die each week, and revealed that the US dropped from 8,891 newspapers in 2005 to 6,377 at the end of May 2022.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] The debate has become more urgent lately, as the 2008–2009 recession shaved newspapers' profits and as once-explosive growth in web revenue has leveled off, forestalling what the industry hoped would become an important source of revenue.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] At issue is whether the newspaper industry faces a cyclical trough (or dip), or whether new technology has rendered print newspapers obsolete.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] As of 2017, an increasing percentage of millennials get their news from social media websites.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the 2010s, many traditional newspapers have begun offering "digital editions", accessible via computers and mobile devices.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] Online advertising allows news websites to show catered ads, based on a visitor's interests.
[src:aachener-zeitung/daily-newspaper] In the web era, digital archives have been continually supplanting earlier microform and hard copy archives, and the latter two media have increasingly been digitized via image scanning, usually in concert with optical character recognition.
